    <h2>Workshop List</h2>
    <p>
        <p><b>W1 - Partnering with Madison Avenue: How to profit from the prominence of games</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 9:30 AM - 11:30 AM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Games are fast becoming the advertising vehicle of choice for marketers keen on reaching the sought-after 18- to 34-year-old male demographic. But it takes a sharp eye to know what ad strategy works best for your game, as well as how to communicate with media buyers and marketers. The importance of developing an intelligent ad-based approach, however, cannot be overlooked. The Yankee Group sees these ad revenues jumping to $800 million by 2009. The Matrix Online and Splinter Cell: Chaos Theory will soon include streaming ads. Shockwave.com recently announced its own in-game ad solution. And there's talk of Spectator Mode on Xbox Live replete with ads that appear during widely watched game matches. This session will look at current ad models, including in-game and around-game ads, product placement, and advergaming. Which agencies are committed to games? How is pricing determined, and what are typical budgets? How does the technology work? How are gamers reacting? Are measuring tools delivering quantifiable results? Are advertisers getting the results they anticipated? Hear from the publishers, developers, brands, and agencies actively leveraging the role games play in the lives of consumers. What ad models are working best, and how can the game industry drive additional revenues from ads without compromising gameplay?&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Michael Goodman, Senior Analyst, Media & Entertainment Strategies - Yankee Group&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Arden Doss, Managing Director - Propaganda GEM<br>Louis A. Figueroa, Director of Business Development & In-Game Advertising - Sony Online Entertainment<br>Julie Shumaker, Director of  Videogame Advertising - Electronic Arts<br>Craig Allen, Chief Executive Officer - Spark Unlimited (Call of Duty: Finest Hour)<br>Kevin Browne, General Manager, New Media & Franchise Development, Xbox Live - Microsoft Corporation<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W2 - Casual games update: How new business models are accelerating the growth of today's game marketplace</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 9:30 AM - 11:30 AM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 406AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">When a casual game strikes a chord with the public, the results can be phenomenal, often providing greater margins than those associated with costly PC or console games. And as broadband access becomes more pervasive, new business models have appeared to support the development of a new crop of casual games. This session will discuss what it takes to create a compelling, original, and profitable casual game. What new business models are driving revenues? Are "advanced casual games" more profitable than traditional titles? What impact are in-game ads having on the casual sector? What's behind the talk of VC-funded roll-ups of small independent casual game studios? How are casual games branching out into mobile, portable, and CD-ROM formats? What distribution channels are available and work best? Attend this session and learn how to participate in one of the game industry's fastest-growing market segments--where smaller teams and faster cycles are netting bigger dollars.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">John Welch, President and CEO - PlayFirst, Inc.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Mike Burns, CEO and Chief Creative Officer - Fuel Industries<br>Dave Williams, Chief Marketing Officer & General Manager - Atom Entertainment<br>James Gwertzman, Director of Business Development - PopCap Games<br>Alex St. John, Chief Executive Officer & Co-founder - WildTangent, Inc.<br>James Smith, Producer - Reflexive Entertainment<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W3 - New rules in play: Deciphering the modern-day game deal</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 9:30 AM - 11:30 AM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 408B&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Today's games proudly display their link to the worlds of film, comics, music, and TV. The use of dynamic camera angles points to movie directors and film editors lending their talent to the game industry, and it's no longer a surprise to hear the music of an Oscar-winning composer or headlining rocker playing in a game soundtrack. But it's more than talent that is shared. Intellectual property also makes the jump from one camp to another. Sometimes games make use of worlds from TV and movies, while other times, it's IP from the gameworld that lands on the big screen or TV. As the exchange of talent and properties increases, so does the complexity of the deals. This session will expose the nuts and bolts of the deal-making taking place behind the scenes. Who gets the biggest share of the pie when a video game is optioned or eventually turned into a movie? What is Hollywood looking for from a video game storyline? How does the game industry make contact with IP owners, musicians, voice actors, and screenwriters? What can game publishers expect to pay to license IP that originated on TV or in the recording studio? A panel of legal, negotiating, representation, and business development experts will reveal how the industries value and monetize talent and IP, how deals are structured, and how to guard against disaster.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Joshua Grode, Partner - Liner Yankelevitz Sunshine & Regenstreif LLP&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Germaine Gioia-Horner, Vice President of Licensing - THQ, Inc.<br>Cody Alexander, Head of Video Games - William Morris Agency<br>Patrick O'Brien, Vice President Business Affairs - Electronic Arts<br>Carianne Brown, Director of Motion Picture and Television Music - Universal Music Publishing<br>Tim Riley, Worldwide Executive of Music - Activision, Inc.<br>Leighton Webb, Vice President, Internatinal Wireless - Fox Mobile Entertainment<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W4 - From Sputnik to Spore: Will Wright's new way of game creation</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 11:45 AM - 12:45 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Maxis Studios founder, Sim City and Sims creator, and uber game designer Will Wright is expanding his gig into anthropology, astronomy and astrobiology. His upcoming game, Spore, will give players a chance to build their character-organism from bones to brains, and allow a gamer to explore the galaxy beginning as a single-cell life form. Interviewed by Newsweek editor N'Gai Croal, topics addressed will include the future of user-generated and shared game content, and the overall process of bringing an impossible idea to reality via an uncompromising approach to game design.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Speakers:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Will Wright, Designer - Maxis (Spore)<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W5 - The Rise of Mobile Entertainment: Upcoming trends and new opportunities in mobile games, music, and TV</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 11:45 AM - 12:45 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 406AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">After years of steady progress, the mobile content market is about to experience a spike in growth. 3D gaming, next-gen handsets, connected devices, and new channel models will provide exceptional market entry opportunities for the intelligent business person. The special Lunchtime session invites Seamus McAteer, Chief Product Architect and Senior Analyst from M:Metrics (a measurement firm specializing in consumer habits and trends in mobile content and mobile applications) to share his most current data. McAteer will focus on 3D and next-gen mobile devices, but will also detail changing consumer preferences and evolving carrier-publisher business models. What changes are afoot in technology and where are new opportunities emerging? How can the mobile game industry learn from the thriving digital music and TV business models? How is online gameplay changing the rules? And what is the likely impact of marketers who clamor for eyeballs now riveted on their handsets and PDAs? Join Seamus McAteer and become versed in why the smallest screens have the biggest appetite for entertainment—and where opportunity lies ahead.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Speakers:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Seamus McAteer, Chief Product Architect + Senior Analyst - M:Metrics<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W6 - Beyond risk: a modern approach to MMORPG development</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 11:45 AM - 12:45 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 408B&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Among the well-established videogame genres, massively multiplayer role-playing games are among the most profitable, but because of astronomical development and maintenance costs, the market is still underserved--there is still no second World of Warcraft, a single game that generates more than $300 million dollars a month in North America while being played by some 5.5 million subscribers worldwide. The questions are clear: How to tap the worldwide appetite for MMORPGs without breaking the bank? What are consumer trends among MMORPG gamers around the world telling us? How does the industry address the intersection of business issues and gameplay (e.g., subscriptions versus in-game transactions)? And, are there any tricks to streamlining the creative and support processes? This lunchtime session will invite three MMOG specialists to discusses the likely future of MMORPGs: the revolutionist, Bill Turpin, CEO of The Multiverse Network, who believes that giving free technology and distribution to every designer will lead to a creative explosion; the traditionalist John Lee, Managing Director, Global Publishing at NC Soft (Lineage, Lineage II), who plays by the current rules; and MMO consultant (and the session's moderator/panelist) Jessica Mulligan with her experience working on Ultima Online, Asheron's Call, and Ryzom to draw on.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Speakers:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Bill Turpin, Co-founder, President and Chief Executive Officer - The Multiverse Network, Inc.<br>Jessica Mulligan, Author/Consultant - <br>John Lee, Managing Director of Global Publishing - NCsoft<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W7 - Next-gen game design: How the new consoles stack up</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 1:00 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">A new generation of home consoles is here--already in the marketplace or fast approaching. By now, programmers, coders, and designers have logged thousands of hours creating next-gen games. What are their experiences? What has the impact of new technologies been on the production pipeline and studio management? How do developers rate the capabilities, toolsets, firepower, and potential of the Revolution, Xbox 360, and PlayStation 3? And in what ways are the new consoles encouraging innovation? This session will take attendees under the hood of the next-generation consoles to sort out the biggest issues and tackle the biggest questions. How are development costs expected to vary across the platforms? How is the installed base of each new system expected to grow? What level of support can game creators expect from manufacturers? A panel of designers will share what they know about the new systems--the good and the bad.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Trent Ward, Creative Director - Backbone Entertainment&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Clint Hocking, Creative Director - Ubisoft  Montreal<br>Mark Allender, Studio Technical Director - Volition<br>Don Daglow, President and CEO - Stormfront Studios<br>Alain Tascan, Vice President and General Manager - Electronic Arts - Montreal<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W8 - Where games fit into the new digital economy</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 1:00 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 406AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">The digitization of content, increased broadband adoption, and the rise of home entertainment networks are setting the stage for exciting opportunities for the game industry. As entertainment media transitions to an all-digital, on-demand ecosystem, consumer expectations and business models are radically changing. Adding to this growth is an expanding blogosphere, a rise of IM culture, an increase in the uploading and sharing of video and photos, and a monetizing of legal peer-to-peer networks. In this session, executives from the front lines of the emerging entertainment economy will discuss what today's consumer wants out of entertainment, the most effective ways to capture mind and market share, what their strategy is to drive revenue from entertainment markets, and how games figure into their plan. Hear how the shared entertainment experience is evolving and how related industries are able to create mutually beneficial value.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Richard Ow, Director, Games - The NPD Group&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Steve Schnur, Worldwide Executive of Music and Audio - Electronic Arts<br>Vince Broady, Senior Vice President, Games and Entertainment - CNET Networks<br>Rich Wickham, Director, Windows Gaming Business - Microsoft<br>Jennifer MacLean, Senior Director, Games and Entertainment - Comcast Online Communications<br>John Cahill, Director, Game Platforms - Yahoo! Inc.<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W9 - Games get up and go: Getting the most out of the PSP, DS, and upcoming mobile handsets</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 1:00 PM - 3:00 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 408B&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">To keep up with the speed of life, almost all forms of media have gone portable. Music, movies, the Web, and user-created content such as photos and videos have been untethered and are consumed on the go. This shift is not lost on the game industry. The release of new portable and handheld gaming platforms has fundamentally changed the consumer experience. This session will look at the impact these new devices will have on the traditional PC and console sectors. In what ways will devices that use the Web to connect gamers build on the existing user experience? Which games are taking the greatest advantage of these new platforms? How do game development costs and markets differ between the PlayStation Portable, Nintendo DS, and next-gen 3G handsets? And what genres work best for each of the platforms? A panel of developers and publishers will look at the risks and opportunities facing an industry that has moved from the arcade into the home and is now going on the road.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Matthew Bellows, General Manager & Vice President - Floodgate Entertainment&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven"><br>Yuanzhe (Michael) Cai, Director, Broadband & Gaming - Parks Associates<br>Jeremy Wells, Business Development Manager - Vodafone Group Services<br>Kristian Segerstrale, Managing Director - Glu Mobile<br>Guha Bala, President - Vicarious Visions, Inc.<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W10 - Blueprint for a killer title: how the pros do it</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 3:30 PM - 5:30 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 404AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Four studio heads or company founders will put their game-development and studio-management chops on the line. Before the panel meets, each panelist will have accepted an assignment to create a business plan to bring a game to market. Working with a fixed IP and target platform (mobile, PC, PSP, Xbox 360), they will present and defend a strategy that takes their game from concept, to execution, and into gamers' hands. Topics covered will include the genre best suited for the IP and platform, budget implications, appropriate team organization, target demographic, selection of distribution channel, ROI forecast, and why they believe their game will be a hit. The assignment: your company has secured the rights to create "E<sup>3</sup> - The Game," a hypothetical game to be based on the annual computer and videogame confab in Los Angeles. Panel members use real numbers, and standard business practices and terms. No pie-in-the-sky proposals, please. Presentations will be open to scrutiny by the other panelists, who will be invited to interrupt and question the methodology of their co-panelists. Attendees will be given time for questions, so bring your notepads and learn how the industry's most accomplished business executives approach the challenge of delivering their game on time and under budget.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator/Panelist:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Aaron Loeb, Chief Operating Officer - Planet Moon Studios (Infected)&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Karthik Bala, Chief Executive Officer - Vicarious Visions, Inc.<br>Gonzague de Vallois, Vice President Publishing - Gameloft<br>Gordon Walton, Co-Studio Director - BioWare, Austin<br>Randy Pitchford, President - Gearbox Software<br>Scott Brown, President - NetDevil<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W11 - Digital distribution lays down tracks: Where direct-to-consumer game distribution stands today</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 3:30 PM - 5:30 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 406AB&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">For years, the game industry has toyed with the idea of digital distribution. Now, after years of effort, the results are in. Some of the biggest publishers are on board, with many front-line games available online the day they are released. Microsoft offers dozens of titles online, as well as a portfolio of try-before-you-buy games through Xbox Live Arcade. Nintendo's Revolution will offer vintage NES and SNES games via the Web. Other initiatives have appeared as well. GameTap, Steam, EA Downloader, Direct2Drive, and other game services offer their own unique spin, and more are on the way. Warner Bros., BioWare/Pandemic, and Trilogy Studios are among a growing legion of game companies that are pursuing options within the digital distribution value chain. This session will address effective business models for digital distribution. How do the services differ? How can developers get their games into the digital channel? Who is profiting most? And how is the consumer benefiting? The music industry has already seen its own revolution in digital distribution. Get ready: Game distribution isn't far behind.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Gabe Zichermann, Chief Marketing/Strategy Officer - Boonty, Inc.&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Sutton Trout, Vice President, Digital Content, Consumer Products, - IGN Entertainment<br>Royal O'Brien, Founder and CEO - Game xStream<br>Jason Williams, Marketing Director - GoGamer.com<br>Kris Alexander, Sr. Product Manager, Digital Media & Gaming - Akamai<br>Eric Hartness, Senior Director of Marketing - EA Nation - Electronic Arts<br>Yoav Tzruya, Chief Operating Officer - Exent Technologies<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br /><p><b>W12 - Game Piracy:  Update on the Latest Strategies to Protect Your Product</b><table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#DEDED"><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Tuesday, May 9, 3:30 PM - 5:30 PM&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">Room 408B&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td class="tableRowEven" colspan="2">The piracy of video games is a significant problem confronting the industry even as it continues to grow.  The increase in broadband access to the Internet in the United States and abroad has increased people's ability to download digital products, including game files.  While there may be commercial opportunities created by this growth, there has also been a rise in the abuse and infringement of game products.  Game piracy
also manifests itself overseas where there are international enterprises and organizations engaged in large-scale manufacture and exportation of pirate versions of game products to countries all over the world, with some countries experiencing piracy levels of over 75 percent. The industry has responded in many different ways to meet the challenge of game piracy but, because of a number of factors, it has continued to persist on a number of fronts, including in the United States.  This session will provide attendees with a number of different perspectives on the game
piracy problem in an effort to shed some more light on this complex topic and to offer some approaches and strategies that have been taken
to address it.  A panel of experts from within the game software industry as well as from law enforcement will each offer their own
unique insights on steps that can be taken to prevent piracy, as well as what is being done to fight the piracy of a video game once it has been released.
&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Moderator:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Chunnie Wright, Senior Anti-Piracy Counsel - Entertainment Software Association (ESA)&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td width="18%" class="tableRowEven">Panelists:</td><td class="tableRowEven">Jasper Smith, Director of Investigations - IPSA International, Inc.<br>Mark Litvack, Partner - Mitchell, Silberberg & Krupp<br>Andrew Myers, Special Agent - FBI - San Francisco, California<br>Thomas Loeser, Assistant U.S. Attorney - U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California<br>Phil Terzian, Director, Government and Legislative Affairs - Activision, Inc.<br>Todd Hollenshead, CEO and Co-owner - id Software, Inc.<br>&nbsp;</td></tr></table></p><br /><br />
    </p>
